{{refimprove|date=September 2016}} [[Image:Esempio di hogen fuda.jpg|thumb|right]] A {{nihongo|'''dialect card'''|lead=yes|方言札|hōgen fuda}} was a system of punishment used in Japanese regional schools in the post-[[Meiji period]] to promote standard speech. It was modelled after similar policies in Europe, {{citation needed span|text=particularly the French ''[[Vergonha]]''.|date=September 2016}}
During the [[Edo period]] under the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] most Japanese people could not travel outside of their home [[Han system|domain]]. As a result, regional [[Japanese dialects]] were relatively isolated and became increasingly distinct. After the [[Meiji Restoration]] the government, in emulation of the European nation states, sought to create a standard Japanese speech. A [[Tokyo dialect]], specifically that of the upper-class [[Yamanote and Shitamachi|Yamanote area]] became the model for [[Standard language|Standard]] Japanese, widely used in schools, publishing, and radio broadcasting. By the early twentieth century, the [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology|Ministry of Education]] and other authorities instituted various policies to reduce or suppress regional differences.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gottlieb|first=Nanette|title=Language and Society in Japan|year=2005|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-53284-1}}</ref>
The use of Hogen fuda was most prominent in the [[Tōhoku region|Tōhoku]], [[Kyushu]] and [[Ryukyu Islands]] (including [[Okinawa]]) as they are geographically and linguistically most distant from the Tokyo dialect. The issue is most prominent in regard to [[Ryukyuan languages]] as there are groups, such as the [[Kariyushi Club]], which advocate the languages to be officially recognised by the Japanese government as a language (and Ryukyu as a nation). {{citation needed span|text=While many mainland regional "dialects" in Japanese are also unintelligible and at least the [[Tsugaru dialect|Tsugaru "dialect"]] in north is considered just as distinct as Ryukyuan, there is no movement in mainland Japan for regional dialects to be recognised as languages.|date=December 2016}}
In Okinawa, the card was initially voluntarily adopted by Okinawan students at the start of the 20th century, but became mandatory as assimilation policies increased following 1917. A student who spoke [[Okinawan language|Okinawan]] would be forced to wear the card, until another student also spoke in Okinawan, and then it would pass to the new transgressor, with the student wearing it at the end of the school day punished by the teachers.<ref name="NoguchiFotos2001">{{cite book|author1=Mary Goebel Noguchi|author2=Sandra Fotos|title=Studies in Japanese Bilingualism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lDBCqwLfp8UC&pg=PA72|accessdate=9 June 2012|year=2001|publisher=Multilingual Matters|isbn=978-1-85359-490-8|pages=72–}}</ref><ref name="Tipton1997">{{cite book|author=Elise K. Tipton|title=Society and the State in Interwar Japan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pvoXnnI0Kf4C&pg=PA204|accessdate=9 June 2012|date=2 October 1997|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-15069-9|pages=204–}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Welsh Not]], a similar punishment for Welsh-speaking students * [[Symbole]], a similar punishment for Breton-speaking students
