The '''Museum of New Mexico''' is a system of museums, historic sites, the Laboratory of Anthropology, the Office of Archaeological Services, the Museum of New Mexico Press, and archaeological collections governed by the State of New Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Mexico Administrative Code|url=http://164.64.110.239/nmac/parts/title04/04.051.0001.htm|publisher=The Commission of Public Records|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>
==History== The Museum of New Mexico was established on February 19, 1909 by the New Mexico Territorial legislature. This pre-statehood legislation mandated that the Museum of New Mexico be housed in the historic [[Palace of the Governors]]. An unusual arrangement existed with the privately-funded [[School of American Archaeology]] in which the School was allowed to occupy the Palace of the Governors free of rent and the Director of the School would serve as the Director of the Museum.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Elliott|first1=Malinda|title=The School of American Research : A History|date=1987|publisher=School of American Research}}</ref> This arrangement lasted until Governor [[John Burroughs (governor)|John Burroughs]] signed a bill on April 2, 1959 forcing the School of American Research to leave state property and the Board of Regents. Over the years, the Museum of New Mexico grew to include the [[New Mexico Museum of Art]], [[Laboratory of Anthropology]], [[Museum of International Folk Art]] and the historic sites of [[Coronado Historic Site|Coronado]], [[Fort Selden]], [[Bosque Redondo Memorial|Bosque Redondo Memorial at Fort Sumner]], [[Jemez Historic Site|Jémez]], [[Lincoln Historic Site|Lincoln]], and [[El Camino Real Historic Trail Site]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Museums and Historic Sites|url=http://www.museumofnewmexico.org/index.php|website=Museum of New Mexico|publisher=New Mexico Department of Cultural Affairs|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> The Museum of New Mexico has been reorganized several times, most recently in 2004 when Governor [[Bill Richardson]] created the [[New Mexico Department of Cultural Affairs|Department of Cultural Affairs]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hartley|first1=Cody|title=Art in an Arid Climate : The Museum of New Mexico and the Cultivation of the Arts in Santa Fe|date=2005|publisher=University of California|location=Santa Barbara|pages=208-209}}</ref>
